    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3362858290" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3362858290" />
    <a title="Steve R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r"><img alt="Steve R" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550608435p2/51602729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3362858290?book_show_action=true">Jun 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve R" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r">Steve R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3362858290" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6354327054530952386">As one of Balzac‚Äôs longer novels, this one exemplifies all of his outstanding strengths: a marvelous ability to delineate characters of variant physical, emotional, intellectual and above all moral natures (just one example: a nefarious lawyer is described as a torpid viper with magpie eyes); his astounding skill in weaving plots so complex yet still understandable, often involving minute financial details and always conflicting elements of personal vanity and ambition; and finally, his setting </span>
  <span id="freeText6354327054530952386" style="display:none">As one of Balzac‚Äôs longer novels, this one exemplifies all of his outstanding strengths: a marvelous ability to delineate characters of variant physical, emotional, intellectual and above all moral natures (just one example: a nefarious lawyer is described as a torpid viper with magpie eyes); his astounding skill in weaving plots so complex yet still understandable, often involving minute financial details and always conflicting elements of personal vanity and ambition; and finally, his setting up of good and bad forces of altruistic idealism and selfish egoism, putting them in play against one another, and leaving the reader hoping against hope that the good guys will win. After the dozen or so of Balzac‚Äôs works I‚Äôve read, I‚Äôve come to always expect an eventual disappointment of failed dreams: he seems to have a predisposition for seeing the naivety of those who innocently expect the best of their fellow men as an inevitable weakness allowing the cynical, self-serving machinations of the greedy to defeat them.<br /><br />Set in both the capital of Paris and a remote province of France, the novel is replete with descriptions of the various social and political forces at play during the Restoration period following the Napoleonic wars. The nose-in-the-air aristocrats are there, with their staunch religiosity and fervent belief in the monarchy. The grasping bourgeoisie appear, largely represented by the generally despised professions of journalism, book publishing, money lending and law. It would appear Balzac himself had poor experiences both in reading his daily newspaper and in dealing with publishers, as there is little to admire in his portrayal of the practitioners of these trades. The supposed social class opponents are quite similarly portrayed: characters of both upper and middle classes are vainglorious, jealous, disloyal, conniving, and always looking for the edge that will put them ahead of their peers.<br /><br />The childlike naivety of Lucien and the blinkered determination of the printer-turned-inventor David provide the basis of ‚ÄòTwo Poets‚Äô, the first of the novel‚Äôs three sections. The precipitous ups and downs of fortune for Lucien in Paris form the basis of ‚ÄòA Provincial in Paris‚Äô, the second part; while the culmination of the fates of David and his loving wife, Eve, who has more brains and awareness of the forces arrayed against them than both her husband and his friend put together, forms ‚ÄòEve and David‚Äô, the final part. It is a masterfully complex, highly dramatic and quite suspenseful story during which I found myself metaphorically booing the bad guys, yelling at the stupidity of their victims, and cheering on the noble efforts of those who strove to save them from their fate. The culmination is, though somewhat blunted, well worth the time it takes to read the roughly 600pp. which it takes one to get there.<br /><br />Part way through the work, in an almost offhand comment, Balzac refers to ‚Äòthe bourgeois taste for literature without ideas‚Äô. This got me wondering if he had inadvertently shown his true colours. For such a master of characterization, of social scene painting and even of psychological analysis, there is a relative shallowness to all the themes presented. Really, other than the fact that some people are not to be trusted and are largely out to take advantage of others for their own selfish ends, I found little depth to the moral arguments presented. Even the Abbe‚Äôs Machiavellian perorations to Lucien which thematically bring the novel to a close seem to present quite a simplistic outlook: ‚ÄòWe are all slaves to something, either a failing or a necessity and must proceed by stealth against others to achieve our desires. Society has usurped so many rights over the individual that he is compelled to act in self defense.‚Äô Even assuming that these ‚Äòrights‚Äô had ever really existed, I would say that this ‚Äòdo it to them before they do it to you‚Äô philosophy is one that someone with such understanding of the workings of men and women in his society could have improved upon.<br /><br />Still, the novel is extremely engaging and exceptionally well crafted. It is just a shame that such fine brush work could not have resulted in a more moving and insightful canvas.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6354327054530952386" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


