<div id="review_2165822063" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2165822063" />
    <a title="Gabrielle Dubois" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28233498-gabrielle-dubois"><img alt="Gabrielle Dubois" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1510402879p2/28233498.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2165822063?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gabrielle Dubois" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gabrielle Dubois" href="/user/show/28233498-gabrielle-dubois">Gabrielle Dubois</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28233498-gabrielle-dubois?shelf=19th-century">19th-century</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2165822063" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6668011197815121714">Balzac said about his Lost Illusions that they were &quot;the main work in the work&quot;. It&apos;s a novel about the functioning of the &quot;literature machine&quot;.<br/>Lucien, a young poet from Angoul√™me, local but not very big fame, is taken to Paris by his protector Mme de Bargenton. In Paris, all the illusions are allowed to him, which doesn‚Äôt mean that they will necessarily become realities.<br/><br/>Balzac, work and money.<br/>To make a fortune was the eternal thought of Balzac. He ran after gold and money while creditors and ba</span>
  <span id="freeText6668011197815121714" style="display:none">Balzac said about his Lost Illusions that they were "the main work in the work". It's a novel about the functioning of the "literature machine".<br />Lucien, a young poet from Angoul√™me, local but not very big fame, is taken to Paris by his protector Mme de Bargenton. In Paris, all the illusions are allowed to him, which doesn‚Äôt mean that they will necessarily become realities.<br /><br />Balzac, work and money.<br />To make a fortune was the eternal thought of Balzac. He ran after gold and money while creditors and bailiffs ran after him and Balzac hid from them to work like a Vulcan on his forge.<br />Excerpt from the Illusions: "My God! my kingdom for gold!" said Lucien to himself, "gold is the only power in front of which everyone kneels." No! his conscience shouted to him, "Glory, is the power, and glory is work! Work! In launching his enraged words, he dined poorly at Hurbain's restaurant."<br /><br />Balzac and the food.<br />Big coffee drinker, Balzac didn‚Äôt always have enough to feed himself or feed those he invited to dine at home. So sometimes Balzac fed on illusions, and it was up to his guests to do the same; but they didn‚Äôt regret it because a conversation with Balzac fed their brains more than a thousand meals would have fed their stomachs!<br />Excerpt from the Illusions: "There are few students housed in the Quartier Latin who haven‚Äôt eaten in Flicoteaux's restaurant, this temple of hunger and misery. What, no doubt, prevented Flicoteaux, this friend of the youth, from making a colossal fortune, is an article he had printed in large letters: BREAD AT DISCRETION, that is to say, until indiscretion. Many glories had Flicoteaux for foster father."<br /><br />Balzac and fashion.<br />Balzac had a taste or didn‚Äôt have any... But for a long time he appeared in Paris wearing a singular blue suit which his astonished and amused contemporaries remembered in their memoirs. Because of the lack of money, of the sake of wearing out his costumes or for a personal taste and comfort, Balzac opted for a simple cream linen dress looking like a monk‚Äôs suit, in which he had himself painted. But as the suit doesn‚Äôt make the writer, his didn‚Äôt prevent him from producing a masterly work.<br />Excerpt from the Illusions: "After the sad test of the elegant life which had absorbed all its capital, Lucien threw himself into work with that first ardor that dispels so quickly the difficulties and the amusements that Paris offers to all the existences, the richest, like the poorest, and who, to be tamed, demand the savagery of true talent or the bleak desire of ambition."<br /><br />Balzac and the publishers.<br />Excerpt from a letter written to a friend by Balzac when he was twenty-four: "For my novel Wann-Chlore, they offer me, guess what? 600 francs! I would rather go to plow the earth with my nails than to consent to such an infamy."<br />Excerpt from the Illusions: Mr. Doguereau was an old school bookseller, a man of the time when the booksellers wanted to hold locked in an attic Voltaire and Montesquieu dying of hunger. After reading Lucien's manuscript, the librarian wants to publish it. "Doguereau came to the hotel where Lucien lived. He was determined to pay one thousand francs... Seeing the hotel, the old fox changed gradually his mind. A young man living there has only modest tastes, I can give him only eight hundred francs. Lucien is a handsome boy, if he earned too much money he would have fun with it, he wouldn‚Äôt work anymore. In our common interest, I will offer him six hundred francs..."<br /><br />In The Lost Illusions, we find Balzac's detailed descriptions of a provincial town, its local bourgeoisie, traders and entrepreneurs. Balzac also paints us the Parisian fauna: noble and rich people, booksellers, journalists, mondains, poor poets, a youth hungry for earthly, intellectual and makeshift food. The author puts himself in the spirit of each of his characters and we sit with Balzac in a provincial salon, we walk with him on a Parisian sidewalk, we dine with him in a poor restaurant, we feel with him the humiliation of being poor in Paris when we were rich in the provinces.<br />√î how I understand the Parisian part of The Lost Illusions! "Unfortunately, it‚Äôs necessary to show off before to be," said Theophile Gautier, and the Lucien by Balzac feels cruelly this quote!<br />The big question asked by Balzac is: does literature have to have a price, and if yes, what price?<br />You think I told you everything about The Lost Illusions? Far from it! But it's so exhausting to make these comments in English... but I like to kill myself with work!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6668011197815121714" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


